{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516531"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12646"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12646"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.09,0.67,0.12,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5128"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110101"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5128"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12646"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92399"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1875"},{"type":"tags","id":"2058"},{"type":"tags","id":"2665"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11637"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12732"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45017"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110101"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old Indigenous Australian man presents to the General Practice clinic for review prior to a planned tooth extraction. The patient has a history of acute rheumatic fever as a child. He is otherwise in good health and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. On auscultation of heart sounds, a low-pitched mid-diastolic murmur located at the apex and loud S1 can be heard. Examination is otherwise unremarkable. He is advised that he will require antibiotic coverage for the dental procedure to prevent cardiac complications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibiotics would be the most appropriate for prophylactic cover?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clindamycin","Azithromycin","Amoxicillin","Cephalexin","Gentamicin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute rheumatic fever (ARF) is a risk factor for the development of rheumatic heart disease (RHD). Half of all patients with ARF will go on to develop RHD within 10 years, though most are asymptomatic. Many patients can develop mixed valvular disease (mitral stenosis and mitral regurgitation) or multi-valve disease (aortic regurgitation and mitral regurgitation). Whilst mitral stenosis is the most common valvular complication of RHD, pure mitral stenosis can occur, as in this case. Mitral stenosis has a characteristic low-pitched mid-diastolic murmur and causes a loud S1 due to the stiffened valve leaflets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECertain dental procedures can cause transient bacteraemia. For patients with valvular heart disease, this increases the risk of infective endocarditis. Australian guidelines recommend that all patients with rheumatic heart disease undergoing such procedures should be given prophylactic antibiotics, after studies demonstrated rheumatic heart disease as an independent risk factor for infective endocarditis. Any bacteraemia that may be associated with dental procedures usually involves viridans group streptococci.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENote that endocarditis prophylaxis is recommended only for patients with a relevant cardiac condition (such as rheumatic heart disease) who are undergoing dental procedures involving manipulation of the gingival or periapical tissue or perforation of the oral mucosa. This includes extractions, implant placement, biopsy, removal of soft tissue or bone, subgingival scaling and root planing, and replanting avulsed teeth. Other dental procedures, such as routine anaesthetic injections through non-infected tissue, taking dental radiographs, or placement of removable prosthodontic or orthodontic appliances, do not require endocarditis prophylaxis. Surgical antibiotic prophylaxis may still be indicated for some oral maxillofacial procedures, even if endocarditis prophylaxis is not.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line choice and appropriate for this patient. It is effective against viridans streptococci. The recommended prophylactic dose is 2g (50 mg/kg up to 2g maximum) orally, 60 minutes prior to the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECephalexin\u003C/strong\u003E is an acceptable second-line choice that would be indicated for patients that have a delayed and nonsevere hypersensitivity to penicillins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be used for patients that have an immediate or severe hypersensitivity to penicillin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAzithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended due to the high percentage of azithromycin-resistant bacteria in normal oral flora.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly used in combination with a penicillin for the \u003Cem\u003Etreatment\u003C/em\u003E of infective endocarditis. However, it has no role in prophylactic cover prior to a dental procedure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antibiotic prophylaxis must always be considered for patients with known rheumatic heart disease and for whom a surgical or dental procedure is planned.","Amoxicillin is the first-line antibiotic for prophylaxis against infective endocarditis in patients with rheumatic heart disease undergoing dental procedures."],"references":["Prevention of Infective Endocarditis. Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. 2025 Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ralph AP, Currie BJ. Therapeutics for rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease. Aust Prescr. 2022 Aug;45(4):104-112. doi: 10.18773/austprescr.2022.034. Epub 2022 Aug 1. PMID: 36110174; PMCID: PMC9427630. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36110174/","Shah SN, Sharma S. Mitral Stenosis. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613493. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28613493/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92399"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12646"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92399"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-28T12:02:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-28T12:02:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5128"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110101"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data